{"key":"processedPost-12715673","value":{"id":12715673,"first":12685150,"last":12715673,"when":1276119470,"utime":"06/10/10 12:37 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /> So we prepared a bulk substrate for the spawn run using organic composted manure from a garden supply pasteurized in a big pot with a pillowcase for 2 hours at 160 - 175F<br /></blockquote><br /><br />That's probably the problem.&nbsp; You can use composted cow manure, if you'll mix it 50/50 with vermiculite.&nbsp; Otherwise it turns to mud and the mycelium can't penetrate it well.&nbsp; In addition, pasteurizing already composted manure in a pillowcase leaches all the goodness that's left in it, right out into the water where it's discarded.&nbsp; So, not only are you starving your mycelium from leaching the nutrients out, but the mycelium is having a hard time due to the density.<br /><br />In addition, proper pasteurization temperature is 140F to 160F, so your minimum temperature was right at the maximum.&nbsp; This means you partially sterilized the manure, killing off beneficial microbes.&nbsp; You should also not pasteurize, even at 140F, longer than 90 minutes.&nbsp; 60 minutes is plenty.&nbsp; I'd suggest bringing your substrate mix to field capacity moisture content and then load into jars and pasteurize in a pot of hot/boiling water as shown in the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Horse-Manure-Substrate\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">horse manure prep</a> sample video clip on my website.<br /><br />Furthermore, if you're keeping the room the substrate is located at 82F, that's way too hot.&nbsp; Mycelium growth slows down at any temperature above 82F, so even a small amount of mycelium-produced heat takes it above the level of optimum growth. I've seen bulk substrates produce 20F above ambient temperature. You need to colonize small substrates at normal room temperature, and large substrates should be colonized at slightly below normal room temperature.<br />RR","title":"Re: Bulk Substrate Colonization Ceased"}}